<h3 class="heading"><span class="type">Paragraph</span></h3>
<p>For example, if <span class="process-math">\(y=x^2\)</span> then <span class="process-math">\(\dx{y}=2x\dx{x}\text{.}\)</span>  It stands to reason that if we integrate , we should end up with .  There is a little bit of a complication here, as differentiating <span class="process-math">\(y=x^2+c\)</span> also yields <span class="process-math">\(\dx{y}=2x\dx{x}\)</span> for any constant <span class="process-math">\(c\text{.}\)</span>  Happily, this is the only such complication; if <span class="process-math">\(\dx{f}=\dx{g} \text{,}\)</span> then <span class="process-math">\(f\)</span> and <span class="process-math">\(g\)</span> must differ by a constant.</p>
